## REVIEWARTICLE

## Molecular Insights Into Colorectal Carcinoma

Domenika Ortiz Requena a and Monica Garcia-Buitrago b

a Department of Pathology and Laboratory Medicine, Jackson Health System/University of Miami Miller School of Medicine, Miami, Florida, USA b Department of Pathology and Laboratory Medicine, University of Miami Miller School of Medicine, Miami, Florida, USA

Received for publication September 5, 2020; accepted September 14, 2020 (ARCMED\_2020\_1628).

Colorectal carcinoma (CRC) is one of the most common type of cancers and a leading cause of cancer-related deaths worldwide and in the United States. CRC is a heterogeneous disease with a well-characterized stepwise accumulation molecular alteration associated with adenoma formation and progression to carcinoma. We review the genomic and epigenomic pathways, including chromosomal instability, microsatellite instability, and epigenetic instability or CpG island methylator phenotype, their characteristics, and prognosis. We describe the four consensus molecular subtypes of CRC established by the international Colorectal Cancer Subtyping Consortium, their mechanisms to develop cancer, molecular characterization, clinical features, and prognosis. Finally, we review currently used predictive biomarkers. /C211 2020 Published by Elsevier Inc. on behalf of IMSS.

Key Words: Colon cancer, Genomic classification, Transcriptomic classification, Consensus molecular subtypes.

## Introduction

Colorectal carcinoma (CRC) represents the third most commontype of cancer in the United States in males and females, based on cross-sectional 2012 e 2016 data, and the third deadliest malignancy for both sexes combined, based on 2013 e 2017mortality data, with a mortality rate of 16.6 males and 11.7 females per 100,000 habitants. The death rates have been steadily falling approximately 2% each year over the last decade, probably due to increasing cancer surveillance and better therapy options (1). The American Cancer Society estimates about 147,950 new colorectal carcinoma cases and 53,200 deaths for CRC for 2020 in the United States (2).

The development of CRC has been associated with environmental and genetic risk factors. About 70% of CRCs present as sporadic carcinomas, approximately 25% of the cases are familial carcinomas without a specific inherited pattern. Less than 10% of patients have inherited syndromes, including hereditary nonpolyposis CRC Lynch syndrome (LS), Familial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP), MUTYH-associated polyposis (MAP), and the hamartomatous polyposis syndromes (i.e., Peutz-Jeghers, juvenile polyposis, PTEN hamartoma tumor or Cowden syndrome). In

most of these inherited cases, the causative genetic mutation has been identified, and a test is available to screen the patients (3).

Personal or family history of CRC is associated with a high risk for synchronous and metachronous primary cancer up to 3 e 5% at five or more years after colon resection, requiring close surveillance. Personal history of idiopathic inflammatory bowel disease (IBD), mainly ulcerative colitis, is associated to CRC, with a 0.5% incidence per year after 10 e 20 years post-IBD diagnosis, 1% per year after 20 e 40 years post-diagnosis, and up to 30% risk by the fourth decade of patients with pancolitis (4).

## Molecular Pathways

Genomic and Epigenomic Classification

The sequence from the precancerous adenoma lesion to invasive carcinoma requires an accumulation of somatic and germline mutations that occur during a period of ten years or more (5). Three molecular pathways have been linked to the pathogenesis of colorectal carcinoma, chromosomal instability (CIN), microsatellite instability (MSI), and epigenetic instability or CpG island methylator phenotype (CIMP) (5 e 9).

Chromosomal instability is present in 85% of invasive CRCs and is characterized by imbalances in chromosome number and loss of heterozygosity, unbalancing the oncogene and tumor suppressors equilibrium, and facilitating

the sequential inactivation of APC, DCC/SMAD4, and TP53 genes. CIN results in high levels of DNA somatic copy-number alterations (SCNAs) and DNA amplifications/gains or deletions/losses in a small group of genes. This pathway is characteristic of Familial Adenomatous polyposis (FAP) patients (7).

Microsatellite instability occurs in up to 15% of CRCs and is caused by inactivation of DNA mismatch repair (MMR) genes, including mutL homologue 1 (MLH1), MLH3, mutS homologue 2 (MSH2), MSH3, MSH6 or PMS1 homologue 2 (PMS2). The tumor cells with defective DNA MMR build up genome errors that further will be repeated, causing hypermutation affecting a large number of genes. A high level of microsatellite instability (MSI-H) is characteristic of Lynch syndrome. The most common MMR-deficient pattern is the loss of MLH1/PMS2 expression due to MLH1 defect, most likely secondary to promoter hypermethylation rather than an MLH1 mutation of Lynch syndrome. Loss of expression of PMS2 alone, MSH2, or MSH6 increases a probability for Lynch syndrome and genetic counseling with germline gene sequencing is recommended for these patients (8)(Figure 1).

Epigenetic instability occurs in up to 20% of CRCs and is associated with widespread hypermethylation of the promoter CpG island loci (CIMP) that results in the inactivation of more than 100 tumor suppressor and/or tumorrelated genes and a very high mutation rate (ultramutant) affecting a large number of genes by mostly passenger mutations and few CRC driver mutations. The CpG

hypermethylation of DNA could activate the BRAF gene or silence the expression of the MLH1 gene (9).

Conventional tubular or tubulovillous adenomas are driven by the CIN pathway (84%) with alterations on APC, KRAS, TP53, PIK3CA, and SMAD4, or MSI pathway (13%) with defective MLH1 or MSH2 (10). In contrast, sessile serrated lesions have epigenetic instability (CIMP) as the initial pathway, followed by MSI as an optional alternative pathway. A high level of MSI (MSIH) is seen in Lynch syndrome CRCs that originate from adenomas and in some sporadic CRCs that arise from sessile serrated lesions (SSLs) that undergo hypermethylationassociated inactivation of the MLH1 gene. The SSL can progress into favorable prognostic MSI-H/CIMP-positive CRC, whereas MLH1-unmethylated/BRAF-mutated proximal traditional serrated adenoma (TSA) can be the precursor of poor prognostic MSS/CIMP-positive CRC. The distal TSAs show KRAS-mutation and a CIMP-low or CIMPnegative status (Table 1)(10).

The Cancer Genome Atlas (TCGA) study analyzed multiple sets of data, including exome sequence, DNA copy number, promoter methylation, messenger RNA, and microRNAexpression from 276 CRC samples and conducted lowdepth-of-coverage whole-genome sequencing in 97 CRC samples. At the genomic level, CRCs were classified as:

a) hypermutated (15%) that frequently show MSI-H due to hypermethylation and MLH1 silencing (75%) and somatic mismatch-repair gene and polymerase Îµ (POLE)

Transcriptomic Classification

Several studies identified different molecular subtypes based on genomic profiling and hierarchical clustering

and hypothesized to arise through distinct biological pathways and to show different biological and clinical behavior (12 e 14). The International Colorectal Cancer Subtyping Consortium compiled genomic databases comprised of 4151 samples, including the TCGA source, applies unsupervised clustering techniques, and established four Consensus Molecular Subtypes (CMS) with distinct molecular characteristics (Table 2) and different histomorphology (Figure 2)(15 e 20), as follows:

These CRCs are associated with the serrated pathway and exhibit mucinous histomorphology, defined by more than 50% of the tumor is composed of mucin showing from glandular structures to single cells embedded in pools of mucin (9). This group can also exhibit histomorphology of medullary carcinomas with sheets of malignant cells with large eosinophilic cytoplasm, vesicular nuclei, and prominent nucleoli with a syncytial growth pattern and prominent infiltration by lymphocytes and neutrophilic granulocytes.

Group CMS2 (Canonical type): features high chromosomal instability (CIN-H), microsatellite stability (MSS), CIMP-negative phenotype, and APC, p53, or RAS mutations, high expression of epidermal growth fact receptor (EGFR) and overexpression of EGFR2 related to WNT/ MYC signaling activation. These tumors occur in the distal colon and rectum, arise from adenomas, show an intermediate prognosis, and represent about 37% of the CRCs. Histopathologically, they are non-mucinous, gland-forming carcinomas with necrotic luminal debris, prominent desmoplastic reaction, and poor infiltration by immune cells.

Group CMS3 (Metabolic type): characterized by metabolic dysregulation with high glutaminolysis and lipidogenesis, MSS, CIMP-low phenotype, and KRAS and APC mutations, represents about 13% of the cases and has an intermediate prognosis. These tumors are equally distributed along the proximal, distal colon, and rectum. Histologically, the metabolic type CRC range from adenocarcinoma with mucinous features to mucinous adenocarcinomas without immune cell infiltration.

Group CMS4 (Mesenchymal type): exhibits MSS, CpG hypermethylation, TGFb activation, stromal infiltration, epithelial-mesenchymal transition activation, matrix remodeling, and angiogenesis. It represents 23% of CRCs, presents at advanced stages, and shows poorer overall survival related to chemo-resistance. By histomorphology, they are more frequently mucinous adenocarcinomas with extensive infiltration of stromal cancer-associated fibroblasts, high levels of lymphocytes, and macrophages infiltration, and prominent angiogenesis.

An additional 13% of CRC cases show mixed features, probably representing either intratumoral heterogeneity or a transition phenotype.

group showed a high number of follicular helper T cells, memory activated helper T cells, and cytotoxic T cells, and less activated NK cells, gd T cells, macrophages, activated dendritic cells, activated mast cells, and neutrophils. This group also showed depletion of T regulatory cells. The CMS2 group showed helper T cells and memory B cells. The CMS3 group showed low immune activation, demonstrated as a high number of resting memory helper T lymphocytes, nave B lymphocytes, and a low number of macrophages, neutrophils, and activated helper T lymphocytes. The CMS4 group demonstrated the highest proportion of leukocytes related to protumor activity, including M2 macrophages, resting dendritic cells, regulatory T cells, eosinophils, and monocytes (21). Becht E, et al. reported high expression of lymphoid and myeloid cell-specific genes in the CMS1 and CMS4 groups. The CMS1 group demonstrated prominent infiltration by CD8positive cytotoxic T cells and NK cells, whereas the CMS4 group showed a high expression of fibroblastic and endothelial cells (22).

## Predictive Biomarkers

## RAS Genes

The RAS-encoded proteins are a family of GTPase-related proteins involved in cell signal transduction. RAS genes are mutated in up to 50% of sporadic CRCs, including the KRAS, NRAS, and HRAS genes. Activating mutation in RASgenes can cause cell proliferation and tumor formation. KRAS mutations are considered early events as they are observed in 60 e 95%ofnon-dysplastic (hyperplastic polyps) and dysplastic precursors lesions. The single nucleotide point mutations that occur in the KRAS gene codons 12 and 13 of exon 2, as well as codon 61 of exon 3, result in activation of the RAS/MAPK signaling pathway and the PI3KAKT pathway. NRAS mutations are found in up to 10% of CRCs. The absence of mutations in KRAS and NRAS (exons 2, 3, and 4) is associated with benefit of treatment with antiepidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR) targeting antibodies, Cetuximab or Panitumumab (23). Several studies have reported that lack of KRAS mutation is associated with decreased metastasis and longer survival (24).

## BRAF Gene

BRAF, an oncogene of the RAF threonine kinases, codifies for a serine/threonine kinase and is activated by its interaction with RAS-GTP. The BRAF gene mutations are encountered in up to 12% of CRC and among these, up to 90% show a V600 E missense mutation, which implies an exchange of glutamic acid for valine in the codon 600 (26), which cause activation of the MEK pathway independent of KRAS. BRAF mutation is found in less than 10% of sporadic CRC and in 31 e 83% of sporadic MSI-H cancers.

BRAF mutations are of use to rule out Lynch syndrome in MSI-H CRCs. BRAF mutations have been encountered in 74% of serrated polyps and up to 82% of serrated carcinomas. With rare exceptions, the RAS and BRAF mutations are mutually exclusive. KRAS mutations are commonly seen across all CRC subtypes, but BRAFV600 E mutations are overrepresented in MSI and CIMP-high tumors. Several studies have reported CRC that are wild type for KRAS, NRAS, BRAF, and PIK3CA (quadruple negative) are more likely to respond to anti-EGFR targeted therapy (25).

## Microsatellite Instability Status

Microsatellite stable CRCs represent up to 70 e 85% of cases. MSS colorectal cancers are molecularly heterogeneous, driven by diverse mechanisms such as extensive DNA methylation, oncogenic mutations in KRAS or BRAF, or chromosomal instability. Multiple studies have reported a worse prognosis in MSS tumors when compared to MSI-high tumors (26,27).

The prevalence of MSI-H in CRC is about 15% in stage II, 8% in stage III, and 4 e 5% in stage IV. MSI decreases the benefit of fluorouracil-based chemotherapy. Recently, studies have demonstrated response of MSI CRC to PDL1 checkpoint inhibitors in patients who failed the first line of treatment.

## Immune Markers

Recent studies have reported complex associations between tumor molecular characteristics and immune cells in the tumor microenvironment. Hypermutated CRCs with high lymphocytic infiltrates, comprised of CD8-positive cytotoxic T cells and T helper1 cells with an interferong immune profile, show upregulated expression of immune checkpoint molecules, including PD-1, PD-L1, CTLA-4, LAG3, and indoleamine 2,3-dioxygenase, and have better relapse-free and overall survival. MSI is a major predictive biomarker for the effectiveness of immune checkpoint inhibitors in patients with metastatic CRC (28,29). Currently, the anti-PD-1 inhibitor Pembrolizumab can be used as a third-line treatment for MSI-H CRCs.

## Tumor Mutational Burden

Tumor mutational burden (TMB) represents the total amount of somatic coding mutations in a tumor and is considered a novel biomarker for immune checkpoint inhibitors therapy. Elevated TMB has been reported in 8 e 25% of CRCs, about 75% of those correspond to hypermutant tumors that also exhibit MSI-H. One-quarter of CRCs harbor increased TMB and are MSS with mutations in the proofreading genes, mainly the polymerase Îµ (POLE). There is limited data regarding the predictive value of POLE mutations in immune checkpoint inhibitors treatment (11).

## Conclusions

Genomic and epigenomic alterations associated with the stepwise progression from adenoma to carcinoma are crucial to determine therapy and establish prognosis in patients with CRC. Most CRCs arising from tubular adenomas are MSS/CIMP-negative, and wild-type KRAS/ BRAF. In contrast, the majority of carcinomas arising from sessile serrated lesions are MSI-H/CIMP-positive and BRAF mutated. CRCs harboring MSI-H/CIMPpositive/SCNA-low profile have a favorable prognosis, whereas MSS/CIMP-negative/SCNA-high tumors have a worse prognosis. The four consensus molecular subtypes of CRC, CMS1 (Immune type), CMS2 (Canonical type), CMS3 (Metabolic type), and CMS4 (Mesenchymal type), exhibit different MSI, CIMP, BRAF, and KRAS mutation profiles that correlate with different prognosis, where CMS1 has the best prognosis and CMS4 the worst prognosis. MSI-H tumors do not benefit from 5-Fluorouracil-based chemotherapy and will benefit from immune checkpoint inhibitors therapy. Lack of RAS/BRAF/PIK3CA mutations is associated with benefit of anti-EGFR therapy.
